<!-- Story Narrative -->
<section class="story-narrative">
    <h2>The Problem</h2>
    <p>In early 2024, our founding team was building AI agents for production systems. We were excited about the possibilities—agents that could understand context, make decisions, and automate complex workflows.</p>
    <p>But we kept running into the same wall: how do you test something that's non-deterministic? Traditional unit tests couldn't capture semantic correctness. Manual testing didn't scale. And every prompt change felt like walking on eggshells.</p>
    <p>We looked for solutions. Existing testing frameworks weren't built for AI. They expected deterministic outputs, predictable edge cases, and objective pass/fail criteria. None of that applies to AI agents.</p>
    <p>So we built FrameLab.</p>
</section>

<!-- Content Section 1 -->
<section class="content-section">
    <div class="content-inner">
        <div class="content-text">
            <h3>Built for AI, from the ground up</h3>
            <p>FrameLab isn't a traditional testing framework adapted for AI. It's purpose-built from scratch to handle the unique challenges of testing non-deterministic systems.</p>
            <p>We created semantic assertions that understand meaning, not just exact matches. We built intelligent benchmarking that compares performance across models and prompts. We automated regression detection that catches subtle quality degradations.</p>
            <p>Everything is designed around one goal: make AI systems as reliable and testable as traditional software.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="content-visual">
